how to control github account and repositary like creating editing and all through using window powershell cli

Of course. You can manage your GitHub account and repositories directly from the Windows PowerShell CLI by using two main tools together: Git and the GitHub CLI (gh).

  • Git is the version control system that tracks changes to your code.

  • GitHub CLI (gh) is a command-line tool that lets you interact with your GitHub account (e.g., create repos, manage pull requests, and issues).

Here‚Äôs how to set it all up and use it. üßë‚Äçüíª

## 1. Installation and Setup

First, you need to install both Git and the GitHub CLI.

  1. Install Git: If you don't have it, download and install Git for Windows. This will also give you Git Bash, which is another useful command-line tool.

  2. Install GitHub CLI: The easiest way to install gh on Windows is with Winget (which is built into modern Windows). Open PowerShell and run:

    PowerShell
    winget install --id GitHub.cli

  3. Authenticate with GitHub: After installation, you need to log in to your GitHub account from the CLI. Run the following command in PowerShell:

    PowerShell
    gh auth login

    It will guide you through a series of prompts. The recommended method is to log in via a web browser, which is secure and easy.

## 2. Managing Repositories

Here are the most common commands for creating and handling your repositories.

Creating a New Repository

You can create a new repository on your GitHub account and immediately clone it to your machine with one command.

PowerShell
# Syntax: gh repo create <repo-name> [flags]
# Example: Create a new public repository and clone it
gh repo create my-new-project --public --clone

This command creates a new public repository named my-new-project on GitHub, then clones an empty version of it into a new folder with the same name in your current directory.

  • Use --private for a private repo.

  • Use --internal for an internal repo (within an organization).

Cloning an Existing Repository

To work on a repository that already exists on GitHub, you clone it.

PowerShell
# Syntax: gh repo clone <owner>/<repo-name>
# Example:
gh repo clone octocat/Spoon-Knife

This downloads the repository to a new folder on your computer. After cloning, you must navigate into the new directory with cd <repo-name>.

PowerShell
cd Spoon-Knife

Listing Your Repositories

To see a list of your own repositories, use:

PowerShell
gh repo list

## 3. The Basic Git Workflow (Editing and Saving)

Once you have a repository on your local machine, you'll use standard Git commands to manage your changes. This is the typical day-to-day workflow.

  1. Check Status: See which files have been changed.

    PowerShell
    git status

  2. Stage Changes: Choose which changes you want to save. To stage all changes in the current directory, use a period (.).

    PowerShell
    git add .

  3. Commit Changes: Save the staged changes to your local repository history with a descriptive message.

    PowerShell
    git commit -m "Add initial project files"

  4. Push Changes to GitHub: Upload your saved (committed) changes from your local machine to the remote repository on GitHub.

    PowerShell
    git push

## A Complete Example Workflow

Here‚Äôs a full sequence of commands from creating a project to pushing your first change.

PowerShell
# 1. Create a new public repo on GitHub and clone it locally
gh repo create my-awesome-app --public --clone

# 2. Navigate into the new project directory
cd my-awesome-app

# 3. Create a new file (you can also do this with a code editor like VS Code)
New-Item README.md

# 4. Add some text to the file
Set-Content README.md "This is my awesome application."

# 5. Stage the new file for commit
git add README.md

# 6. Commit the staged file with a message
git commit -m "Add README file"

# 7. Push your commit from your computer to GitHub
git push

Now, if you check your GitHub account in a web browser, you'll see the my-awesome-app repository with your README.md file in it! üöÄ

how to edit any repositry

To edit any repository, you first need a copy of it on your local machine. This is called cloning. If it's not your repository, you should fork it on GitHub first, then clone your fork.

Once cloned, the editing process is a simple 3-step cycle using Git commands inside the project's folder in PowerShell.

## 1. Get the Repository on Your PC

First, find the repository on GitHub. Use the gh repo clone command to download it.

PowerShell
# Syntax: gh repo clone <owner>/<repository-name>
# Example for cloning a popular repository from Microsoft
gh repo clone microsoft/terminal

After the download finishes, you must navigate into the newly created folder.

PowerShell
cd terminal

All subsequent commands must be run from inside this folder.

## 2. The 3-Step Editing Workflow ‚úçÔ∏è

After you've made changes to the files using any text editor (like VS Code or Notepad), you save those changes to GitHub using this command cycle.

Step 1: Stage Your Changes

Tell Git to prepare all the changes you've made for saving. The period (.) means "all files in this directory."

PowerShell
git add .

Step 2: Commit Your Changes

Save a snapshot of your staged changes to your computer's local history. You must include a descriptive message about what you changed.

PowerShell
# The -m flag stands for "message"
git commit -m "Fix typo in the documentation"

Step 3: Push Your Changes to GitHub

Upload your committed changes from your computer to the remote repository on GitHub, making them visible to everyone else.

PowerShell
git push

And that's it. You can repeat this add -> commit -> push cycle every time you want to save a new set of edits to the repository.

i want to download just one repo and make change in it

You can do this by cloning the repository to your computer, making your edits, and then pushing those changes back to GitHub. Here's a step-by-step guide.

## Step 1: Clone (Download) the Repository

First, you need to download the repository to your machine. Open PowerShell and use the gh repo clone command. Replace <owner> and <repo-name> with the actual details of the repository you want.

PowerShell
# Clones the repository to a new folder in your current directory
gh repo clone <owner>/<repo-name>

# Example:
gh repo clone learn-powershell/powershell-class

After cloning, you must navigate into the new project folder.

PowerShell
cd <repo-name>

# Example:
cd powershell-class

## Step 2: Make Your Changes

Now you can open this folder with your favorite code editor (like VS Code) or even just Notepad. Add new files, delete old ones, or edit existing files as you wish. This step happens outside of PowerShell.

## Step 3: Save and Upload Your Changes

After editing the files, return to your PowerShell window (which should still be in the project directory) and follow this three-command process to save your work to GitHub. ‚úÖ

  1. Stage the changes. This prepares all your edits to be saved. The . stands for all files.

    PowerShell
    git add .

  2. Commit the changes. This saves a snapshot of your work to your local machine. Write a clear, descriptive message about what you changed.

    PowerShell
    git commit -m "Update the main script with new features"

  3. Push the changes. This uploads your saved commit from your computer back up to GitHub.

    PowerShell
    git push

Your changes are now live in the GitHub repository. You can repeat this add -> commit -> push cycle whenever you make more edits.

PS C:\Users\nishk\documents\github> gh repo clone StarRy7c/Willow-p

Cloning into 'Willow-p'...

error: RPC failed; curl 56 Recv failure: Connection was reset

fatal: fetch-pack: invalid index-pack output

failed to run git: exit status 128

This error means your network connection to GitHub was interrupted while the files were being downloaded. It's a common issue on unstable or slow internet connections and is not a problem with your command or the repository itself.

Here are the most effective solutions, starting with the easiest.

## 1. Perform a "Shallow Clone"

This is the most likely solution to work. A shallow clone downloads only the most recent version of the code, not the entire project history. This means a much smaller download that is less likely to be interrupted.

Since gh repo clone doesn't support this directly, use the standard git command instead:

PowerShell
git clone --depth 1 https://github.com/StarRy7c/Willow-p.git

## 2. Increase Git's HTTP Buffer

Sometimes, Git's default buffer for data transfer is too small, which can cause timeouts. You can increase it with a one-time configuration command.

Run this command in PowerShell:

PowerShell
git config --global http.postBuffer 524288000

This sets the buffer to about 500 MB. After running this, try your original gh repo clone command again.

## 3. Check for Network Interference

A VPN, proxy, or strict firewall can often interfere with the connection.

  • If you are using a VPN, try disconnecting from it temporarily and running the clone command again.

  • If you are on a corporate or university network, their firewall might be interrupting the connection.

## 4. Switch to the SSH Protocol

If the standard HTTPS connection keeps failing, switching to the SSH protocol can sometimes provide a more stable connection.

Note: This method requires you to have set up SSH keys with your GitHub account first.

If you have SSH set up, use this command:

PowerShell
git clone git@github.com:StarRy7c/Willow-p.git

how to control the hieght of iframe video for phone

Of course. You can control the height of the video player on phones by adjusting a specific line in the CSS media query within your Canvas.

The code that controls this is in the <style> section of your index.html file:

CSS
/* NEW - Media Query for Mobile */
@media (max-width: 767px) {
    .video-container {
        height: 55vh; /* Reduced height for mobile */
    }
    .telegram-container {
        padding: 15px; /* Adjust padding for mobile */
    }
}

How to change it:

  • The line height: 55vh; inside .video-container sets the video player's height to 55% of the phone screen's total height.

  • To make the video player taller on phones, increase this number (e.g., height: 70vh;).

  • To make it shorter, decrease this number (e.g., height: 45vh;).

Simply find that @media (max-width: 767px) block in your CSS and change the 55vh value to whatever you'd like.
